@node "Document_0" "Why was this program created?"
@{b}@{u}Why this program was created.@{ub}@{uu}

Nowadays  AmiNet is important for all Amiga owners to share files through. 
With such a great shareware  base, however,  there are many files. With  a 
Ftp-client  like  MuiFtp  by Michael Neuweiler you can easily choose among 
them in their divided drawers, but what happens if you don't have a wallet 
the size of Bill Gates' and can't stay online all day?

Then  you  can  examine  the  files at  home by downloading  the  enormous 
indexfile from AmiNet. This file is pretty hard to handle and difficult to
search in - and that's why Index2Guide were created!

Index2Guide  makes  an  easy to read   .guide-file  out  of  the indexfile,  
which  can  be  read  by  any  program  that  supports the hypertext format 
AmigaGuide such as Multiview that comes with AmigaOS 3.0+.

In the created AmigaGuide file  you can click your  way through the drawers 
and  see  which  files  is  in  each  drawer -  which  is much easier  than 
examining the whole index at a time, and the guide-file gets smaller!

With  version  1.3  you can  convert  RECENT files to AmigaGuide format to.
@endnode

@node "Document_7" "What does this program require?"
@{b}@{u}What this program requires.@{ub}@{uu}

Well... first you got  to  have  an Amiga,  and that's about it! But if you
would like to view result of this program  you must  have  a  program  that
supports the hypertext format AmigaGuide.

ie:  AmigaGuide or Multiview.

This  program  requires  a  lot of  memory. 2 * the  size of  the Indexfile
you   are  converting   or 12 * the  Recent file  (Recent-files are  small, 
though).  If you have problem with this,  write to me,  and I will consider 
releasing a less memory-hungry version.
@endnode

@node "Document_1" "How do I use this program?"
@{b}@{u}How to use the program.@{ub}@{uu}

The using of the program is very simple,  just double-click on it's icon or
start it from Shell/Cli. It no longer takes  arguments  from  cli.

@{b}The mainwindow@{ub}

When  starting  the program,  a  window  appears.  It  has  two  buttons at
the  bottom, a  progress indicator  and some  information about the choosen 
file.

Name    - The name of the file.

Size    - The size of the file.

Type    - What type the file is of. (Recent or Index)

Status  - What the program is doing at the moment.


About   - Button for showing information about the program.

Convert - Start converting your file.

If you have got the "TREE" file in the drawer you start  the  program from,
or   in   S:, "The TREE-file was found"  is   shown  between  the  buttons.
Otherwise  "The TREE-file was NOT found"  is shown.  The "TREE" file can be
found on any AmiNet site or on any AmiNet CDs.

@{b}When converting@{ub}

Pick a correct INDEX file or RECENT file found on AmiNet, or on one of  the
AmiNet CD's, by clicking on the "Convert"-button to the right of the  main-
window.

If the file  is an proper  Index/Recent-file  the  program  will  start  to
analyze it, showing progress on the progress indicator.

If "The file is NOT an AmiNet-file" is displayed, the program is  sure  you
have not given it a AmiNet Index/Recent-file.  Maybe  you have forgotten to
unpack it, or you picked the wrong file.

If "The file is  probably not  an AmiNet-file.  Continue anyway?" is shown,
the  program does  not think  you  have choosen a correct file.  It  is  an  
ASCII-file,  but does  not start  with "|"  as it usually does. Deciding to  
continue here may hang your computer if the file is in an incorrect format.

When the the program is finished, the file created can be found in the same
drawer as the source, but with the extension ".guide".

View  the  new  .guide file with any program that supports AmigaGuide,  and  
you will soon see how useful this program actually is.

@{b}When viewing@{ub}

At  the  start  you  see  a list of the maindrawers at Aminet with,  if the
"TREE"-file was present when the file was converted, descriptions  of  them
are on the right.

If you go ahead and click on one, the subdrawers of the drawer  are  shown.
These can also have descriptions. If you click on one of them,  their files
are displayed. You can go back by clicking on the retracebutton.

In the filelist  you can see @{i}the  name of the file@{ui}  (Oh yeah!;),  @{i}its size@{ui},
@{i}its age@{ui} and  @{i}a short description@{ui}  of the file. If the description has a '+'
in front  of it, there is a  longer  description  available  on AmiNet. The
age  is,  depending on if it's a RECENT or INDEX-file,  in  days  or  weeks
present on AmiNet. A '.' before the age means it is in days.

If you think the abbreviations  of the drawers  (like  'comm'  or  so)  are
cryptic,  you  are  strongly  recommended to download the TREE-file from an
AmiNet site or CD.  Then you will  get an easy to understand description of
the directories.
@endnode

@node "Document_3" "Which files can it convert?"
@{b}@{u}Which files it can convert.@{ub}@{uu}

This program can convert both Index-files and Recent-files of AmiNet. These
files can be converted as long as they look like they do today:

        @{i} The token '|' in front of the non-file-lines

                      19 charaters filename

                      <11 charaters directory
    
                       max 6 charaters size

                       max 6 charaters age

               Less than 80 charaters descriptions

         An extra linefeed between the days in Recent-files.@{ui}


As soon as this is changed, the program must unfortunately change - I would
really appreciate if someone told me when ;).
@endnode

@node "Document_4" "What are the known bugs?"
@{b}@{u}The known bugs.@{ub}@{uu}

There are no real bugs,  but there may exist some unsupported type of Index 
or  Recent files,  as  reported  by  Christer  Bjarnemo (I didn't find that 
one,  however). Please  write  to  me  if any kind  of  bug is  encountered
including unsupported types of AmiNet lists.
@endnode

@node "Document_5" "What is left to be done?"
@{b}@{u}To do.@{ub}@{uu}

Well, here's a list of things:

* Be able to download through the AmigaGuide-file, as suggested by Christer
  Bjarnemo. He has also sent me the software for it - but it would make the
  AmigaGuide-files enormous. Please write and tell me what you think.

* Make size and numbers of files appears next to the drawers.

* Make everything optional.

Please write to me if you have anything to add!
@endnode

